[3] Infection in children
Date: Wed 4 Aug 2021
Source: Forbes [edited]
https://tinyurl.com/r7juyeww


The number of children contracting COVID-19 has increased 5-fold since the end of June [2021], with a "substantial" 84% jump in the last week alone, according to a new report from the American Academy of Pediatrics, which comes as numerous states report upticks in child hospitalizations amid the ongoing delta surge.

The pediatricians' group said on Tue [3 Aug 2021] that it had recorded almost 72 000 new cases of COVID-19 among children from 22-29 July, up from 39 000 the week prior and a sum that accounted for 19% of all cases reported nationally over that period.

As cases among children continue on an upward trend that dates back to early July [2021], a growing number of states are sounding the alarm about the number of children being hospitalized, with many citing a corresponding spike in cases of respiratory syncytial virus (RSV), a contagious seasonal [respiratory infection] that is commoner in the wintertime. Child hospitalizations have risen in at least 8 states, either state-wide or in major pediatric facilities, according to a mix of state and federal data, and local reports.

Florida currently leads the nation in kids hospitalized for COVID-19, with 32 pediatric hospitalizations per day between 24 and 30 July [2021] (a rate of 0.76 children hospitalized per 100 000 residents), CDC data shared with The Tampa Bay-Times shows. However, officials from major childrens' hospitals in Arkansas, Indiana, Louisiana, Missouri, South Carolina and Texas say their facilities are quickly filling with sick children too, either from COVID-19 too or the mix of the 2 surging respiratory infections.

Alabama, which reported a new record of 34 children hospitalized amid the COVID-19 pandemic last week, now has 38 children hospitalized, according to the Associated Press. Major children's hospitals in Alabama, Arkansas, Louisiana and Florida--states that have been battling a broader increase in hospitalizations--all said last week they had more children in their care than at any other point in the pandemic.

As no regularly updated, comprehensive data on child COVID-19 cases are available, it's unclear whether the rise in hospitalizations is occurring nationwide. The last report from CDC, in early June [2021], found hospitalization rates among children peaked at 2.1 per 100 000 in January [2021]. Meanwhile, the American Academy of Pediatrics (which acknowledges it is missing data from some states) reports the number of hospitalizations has remained steady throughout the pandemic, with children accounting for between 1.3% and 3.5% of hospitalizations, depending on the state. Overall, the risk of death and hospitalization among children who contract COVID-19 remains low. Just over 520 children have died from COVID-19 since the start of the pandemic (0.08% of the US's 612 000 total deaths) and only around 0.01% of recorded cases result in death. However, CDC notes that it is still possible for children to suffer from severe disease as it "occurs in all age groups".

Experts have floated numerous explanations for why child hospitalizations appear to be on the rise, with many pointing to the trend of younger people making up a larger proportion of new cases. Children under 12 are also unable to get the vaccine. Meanwhile, inoculations are severely lagging among teenagers and young adults for whom the shot is available.

Whether the combination of surging COVID-19 and RSV cases may overwhelm hospital pediatric units needs to be watched out for. After steadily increasing since early June [2021], cases of RSV saw a larger spike over the past month according to CDC data, prompting concern from some public health experts.

Dr Heather Haq, a pediatrician at Texas Children's Hospital in Houston, recently detailed in a series of Twitter posts how "the surge upon surge" is impacting her facility. "After many months of zero or few pediatric COVID-19 cases, we are seeing infants, children and teens with COVID-19 pouring back into the hospital, more and more each day," Haq wrote, explaining the hospital also has "winter-level patient volumes of acutely ill infants/toddlers with RSV". "I worry that we will run out of beds and staff," she said.

[byline: Jemima McEvoy]

--
communicated by:
Claudinne Miller
Tulane Outbreak News
<cmiller15@tulane.edu>

[Fortunately, deaths in children infected with SARS-CoV-2 are rare. But with the combined increase of children infected with SARS-CoV-2 and RSV, the hospitals will definitely be challenged.

Children have also been reported to be experiencing increased incidence of respiratory syncytial virus, which is historically more often seen in winter. "Cases of RSV (respiratory syncytial virus) have risen gradually since early June [2021], with an even greater spike in the past month, according to data from CDC. The illness, which can cause symptoms that include a runny nose, coughing, sneezing and fever, normally begins to spread in the fall, making this summer spike unusual....Experts there say that children may be more vulnerable than usual to seasonal viruses and infections because they were underexposed to germs during lockdowns early in the pandemic." (from https://www.nytimes.com/2021/08/01/world/delta-variant-kids-infections.html)

"Respiratory syncytial virus has become recognized as a leading global cause of morbidity and mortality, especially amongst infants in the first 6 months of life. [It] is the commonest cause of childhood acute respiratory infection (ARI) and the major single cause of hospitalization during infancy. In recent decades, it has been realized that it also afflicts various at-risk adults, including frail elderly and immunocompromised persons." (from https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK442240/) - Mod.LK]

