[E] Sri Lanka
Date: Thu 5 Aug 2021 08:27 PM IST
Source: Daily Mirror [edited]
https://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/94-COVID-19-deaths-reported-Death-toll-surges-to-4-821/108-217614


Another 94 COVID-19 related deaths that occurred yesterday [4 Aug 2021] were confirmed by the director-general of health services today [5 Aug 2021], pushing the death toll to 4821. According to the Government Information Department, 45 females and 49 males are among the deceased.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-SoAs
<promed-SoAs@promedmail.org>

[Maps of Sri Lanka: http://www.mapsopensource.com/images/sri-lanka-districts-map.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8577773,144.

The South Asian COVID-19 situation, according to data from Worldometer (https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/) as of 6 Aug 2021 at 03:41 GMT:

Country: Total cases / Total deaths / Deaths per million population
India: 31 856 757 / 426 785 / 306
Bangladesh: 1 322 654 / 21 902/ 132
Pakistan: 1 058 405 / 23 702 / 105
Nepal: 708 079 / 9994 / 336
Sri Lanka: 321 429 / 4821 / 224
Afghanistan: 149 806 / 6879 / 172
Maldives: 77 999 / 222 / 403
Bhutan: 2543 / 2 / 3

Over the last 7 days, 284 413, 96 401, 33 544, 17 437, 17 227, and 3283 COVID-19 cases were detected in India, Bangladesh, Pakistan, Nepal, Sri Lanka, and Afghanistan, respectively. This compares with 279 282, 86 053, 24 827, 15 916, 12 904, and 3084 cases in the preceding 7 days, revealing a slow and steady increasing trend still in India and Nepal, the continuation of a sustainable uptrend in Bangladesh, almost a stable trend in Afghanistan, but the development of sharp peaks of new cases in Pakistan and Sri Lanka.

The spread of the delta variant in Pakistan has already been reported.The variant has also been detected in Sri Lanka. A report published in mass media indicates that 75% of the COVID-19 cases detected in Colombo during the last week of July 2021 were caused by this variant. (https://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/75-of-Delta-variant-cases-detected-in-last-week-of-July-from-Colombo/108-217615).

It would not be surprising to see a rapid escalation of the disease situation in these 2 countries because of the massive spread of the highly infectious delta variant, as was seen previously in India and Nepal, and is being currently observed in Bangladesh.

The current proportional case positivity is much higher in Bangladesh than in other South Asian countries. Although the daily case positivity dropped a bit from around 30% recorded over the previous 2 weeks, the total numbers of new cases and deaths both increased in the last 7 days. A total of 264 deaths were reported officially from the country yesterday, the highest single day count since the 1st death reported from the disease in the country on 18 Mar 2020. The disease has perhaps reached its highest peak in this current wave and should recede a bit in the near future thanks to the country-wide lockdown imposed which has been extended to 10 Aug 2021. The results of sequence data of 300 samples from a study in the country revealed the presence of the delta variant in 98% of the samples investigated (https://www.thedailystar.net/health/disease/coronavirus/news/delta-variant-found-98pc-covid-samples-2145851).

Still, there is no clear sign that the slow and steady growth of new cases in India and Nepal, as seen over the last 2 weeks or so, will turn into a significant new wave in the near future. However, this possibility cannot be ruled out, and therefore, both countries should take preemptive measures to avoid it. The total number of deaths in Nepal attributed to the disease is close to the milestone of 10 000.

To compare the situation in South Asian countries above with previous disease data, readers are referred to ProMED-SoAs archives.

The lowest number of confirmed cases recorded so far is from Bhutan (2543), with 2 deaths. - Mod.PKB]

